WEBVTT

00:07.398 --> 00:12.577
♪♪

00:12.621 --> 00:15.754
[ Whispering indistinctly ]Meredith:
Homeostasis is our body's way

00:15.798 --> 00:20.324
of maintaining a consistent
and steady internal state.

00:20.368 --> 00:24.720
♪ Pushin' away
only gets me closer ♪

00:24.763 --> 00:27.288
♪♪

00:27.331 --> 00:28.941
♪ Fallin' fast Nick?

00:28.985 --> 00:30.291
♪ Can we move it slower?

00:30.334 --> 00:31.596
Hi.

00:31.640 --> 00:33.076
Hi.
[ Chuckles ]

00:33.120 --> 00:35.557
Yes, sorry.

00:35.600 --> 00:38.777
This is a very old-fashioned way
to ask a girl on a date.

00:38.821 --> 00:40.040
I know. I know.
I'm sorry.

00:40.083 --> 00:42.172
I-I forgot to ask
for your phone number,

00:42.216 --> 00:43.391
and then I-I didn't want
to wake you.

00:43.434 --> 00:45.958
So...note.

00:46.002 --> 00:48.265
♪ Throw me in the water

00:48.309 --> 00:50.050
So, what do you think --
should we get some dinner?

00:50.093 --> 00:52.922
I know a place that's great.
It's, uh, right by the lake.

00:52.965 --> 00:54.402
Yes.

00:54.445 --> 00:56.186
Okay.

00:56.230 --> 00:58.319
I'll pick you up at 7:00.

00:58.362 --> 01:00.147
Okay.

01:00.190 --> 01:01.322
Okay.

01:01.365 --> 01:02.671
Okay.

01:02.714 --> 01:04.847
I'll see you at 7:00.
Okay.

01:04.890 --> 01:09.243
♪ I know
I'm not getting out alive ♪

01:09.286 --> 01:16.119
♪ Why would I even wanna try?

01:16.163 --> 01:20.776
♪ 'Cause I'm stuck to you

01:20.819 --> 01:23.170
Multiple systems work in sync

01:23.213 --> 01:26.173
to regulate factors like
temperature, blood pressure,

01:26.216 --> 01:27.435
even sodium levels.

01:27.478 --> 01:30.133
♪♪

01:30.177 --> 01:31.700
♪ Are we too far
from the path we drew? ♪

01:31.743 --> 01:34.050
Okay. I'm not going to tell you
how to parent your son,

01:34.094 --> 01:35.573
but this not going
in Luna's bag.

01:35.617 --> 01:37.184
[ Both laugh ]

01:37.227 --> 01:40.274
♪ But I don't wanna be
a fool for you ♪

01:40.317 --> 01:44.843
♪ No, I don't wanna be
a fool for you ♪

01:44.887 --> 01:47.498
These systems are designed
to resist and combat

01:47.542 --> 01:49.761
anything that tries
to throw our bodies off.

01:49.805 --> 01:53.069
♪ I know
I'm not getting out alive ♪

01:53.113 --> 01:57.856
♪ Why would I even wanna try?

01:57.900 --> 02:00.990
It's a continual loop
with checks and balances.

02:01.033 --> 02:03.601
So, what time
did you tell them?

02:03.645 --> 02:05.821
Ahh. Should be
any minute now.

02:05.864 --> 02:07.127
[ Chuckles ]

02:07.170 --> 02:09.520
Feels like the old days.

02:09.564 --> 02:11.087
Finally.

02:11.131 --> 02:12.784
♪ 'Cause I'm stuck to you

02:12.828 --> 02:15.439
Until something manages
to break the cycle.

02:15.483 --> 02:17.789
♪ 'Cause I'm stuck to you

02:17.833 --> 02:19.182
Hi-e-e-e!

02:19.226 --> 02:20.705
How are you so awake?

02:20.749 --> 02:22.359
Kombucha, girl.

02:22.403 --> 02:24.361
[ Yawning ] Remind me why
we signed up to do this again?

02:24.405 --> 02:25.362
To save lives.

02:25.406 --> 02:26.711
Overrated.

02:26.755 --> 02:28.322
Hey, Ortiz,
where's your mom?

02:28.365 --> 02:30.324
She transferred
her residency

02:30.367 --> 02:32.587
to take a job with Dr. Avery
and the foundation.

02:32.630 --> 02:35.111
Good for her.
Better for us.

02:35.155 --> 02:36.286
More cases.

02:36.330 --> 02:37.853
Taryn:
There's no statistical evidence

02:37.896 --> 02:39.855
that proves residents learn
better at the crack of dawn.

02:39.898 --> 02:42.379
I checked. I think we need
to stage a sleep-in.

02:42.423 --> 02:44.381
Who's with me?[ Clears throat ]

02:44.425 --> 02:47.254
[ Indistinct conversations
in distance ]

02:47.297 --> 02:49.430
You finished?

02:49.473 --> 02:51.475
Big day.
And a long one.

02:51.519 --> 02:52.607
Hope you ate breakfast.

02:52.650 --> 02:53.782
[ Quietly ]
We didn't.

02:53.825 --> 02:56.001
Meet me in the skills lab,
four minutes.

02:56.045 --> 03:00.223
[ Woman speaking indistinctly
over P.A.]

03:00.267 --> 03:02.225
He said four minutes. It's
at least an eight-minute walk.

03:02.269 --> 03:05.185
I'm with cardio today.
They requested me.

03:05.228 --> 03:07.012
But have fun
going back to day one.

03:07.056 --> 03:09.493
[ Chuckles ]

03:09.537 --> 03:12.061
Thanks for coming
on such short notice.

03:12.104 --> 03:13.889
Well, I went down
two wrong hallways,

03:13.932 --> 03:16.326
which feels like a metaphor
for my life.

03:16.370 --> 03:17.936
[ Laughs ]But when somebody offers

03:17.980 --> 03:20.852
to pick you up in their private
jet, you get on that jet.

03:20.896 --> 03:22.245
Meanwhile,
Scout has decided

03:22.289 --> 03:24.247
it is no longer cool
to sleep through the night,

03:24.291 --> 03:25.814
so I looked like crap
when I dropped him off to Link,

03:25.857 --> 03:28.991
who has mastered
quiet disappointment.

03:29.034 --> 03:30.384
But somehow
looks so good doing it.

03:30.427 --> 03:32.429
I think you look great.

03:32.473 --> 03:37.260
♪♪

03:37.304 --> 03:40.307
Wait.
Are you kidding?

03:40.350 --> 03:41.743
They're giving you a lab?

03:41.786 --> 03:44.746
Oh, you are definitely
not coming back to Seattle.

03:44.789 --> 03:46.356
By the way, who actually
sent the private jet --

03:46.400 --> 03:48.445
Amelia.

03:48.489 --> 03:52.319
We're being offered millions
of dollars to cure Parkinson's.

03:52.362 --> 03:53.668
Us?

03:53.711 --> 03:56.105
Well, me. But I'm asking you,
so it's us.

03:56.148 --> 03:58.150
♪♪

04:09.771 --> 04:10.859
[ Children laughing ]

04:10.902 --> 04:13.165
Teddy:
Leo says that Elsa needs a cape,

04:13.209 --> 04:15.994
but he shoved it
in the dishwasher last night.

04:16.038 --> 04:17.822
Wasn't great.Well, even Snow Queens

04:17.866 --> 04:20.216
need to learn that actions
have consequences.[ Whispering ] Thanks.

04:20.260 --> 04:22.436
So, is it, um, costume day
or something?

04:22.479 --> 04:24.786
No. Leo's world.
We just live in it.

04:24.829 --> 04:25.830
Oh.[ Cellphone chimes, vibrates ]

04:25.874 --> 04:27.136
Oh.
Incoming trauma.

04:27.179 --> 04:28.180
Okay. I gotta go.Okay.

04:28.224 --> 04:29.486
Teddy.
Yeah.

04:29.530 --> 04:32.272
Allison, Elsa.
I love you.

04:32.315 --> 04:33.273
Bye. Bye. Bye.

04:33.316 --> 04:34.883
Bye.

04:38.234 --> 04:39.453
I'm sorry.
Do you have a problem?

04:39.496 --> 04:41.759
'Cause you're
staring at my kid.

04:41.803 --> 04:43.283
Oh, uh, I'm staring
at his costume.

04:43.326 --> 04:45.633
No, I-I know, and I would
really appreciate if --

04:45.676 --> 04:47.156
Oh, my wife and I have been
looking for that same one

04:47.199 --> 04:48.375
everywhere.

04:48.418 --> 04:50.072
Oh. Oh, yeah.

04:50.115 --> 04:51.856
I-I'll --
I'll ask my husband.Mm.

04:51.900 --> 04:53.118
Oh, uh, here.

04:53.162 --> 04:54.337
Thanks.
Yeah.

04:54.381 --> 04:56.034
Hey. Hi.

04:56.078 --> 04:57.384
We're gonna get you
a new cape, okay?

04:57.427 --> 04:59.821
Luna, it's important work,
okay?

04:59.864 --> 05:02.389
Just stop being so cute
for 5 seconds.

05:02.432 --> 05:04.216
Stop. Stop.

05:04.260 --> 05:06.480
I remember when Scout used to
cry when I dropped him off.

05:06.523 --> 05:08.133
Now look at him.

05:08.177 --> 05:10.048
Basically ready
for his first studio apartment.

05:10.092 --> 05:11.441
[ Whimpers ]

05:11.485 --> 05:12.573
Ow!

05:12.616 --> 05:14.749
Okay. Um,
I'm on scut all day,

05:14.792 --> 05:16.446
so can you just, like,
hop up here

05:16.490 --> 05:18.535
and check on her
every 5 minutes?

05:18.579 --> 05:21.146
Nope. Webber roped me
into a thing with the residents.Ugh.

05:21.190 --> 05:23.888
Luna's like a 36-second
elevator ride away,

05:23.932 --> 05:26.021
if you need to see her.
Plus, they text you pictures.

05:27.327 --> 05:28.415
Go.

05:28.458 --> 05:29.764
Go!
Ugh.

05:29.807 --> 05:31.418
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

05:31.461 --> 05:33.071
Rashida Flowers, 34,

05:33.115 --> 05:35.770
chronic kidney disease
secondary to diabetes,

05:35.813 --> 05:37.772
admitted for dialysis
access insertion

05:37.815 --> 05:39.991
after a thrombosed AV fistula.

05:40.035 --> 05:41.123
Rashida:
After two failed grafts,

05:41.166 --> 05:42.733
I'm back
in the hospital, y'all.

05:42.777 --> 05:44.344
Have to have
another procedure.

05:44.387 --> 05:47.129
But guess what?
My new doctor is a brother.

05:47.172 --> 05:49.392
Mm! And he fly.
[ Laughs ]

05:49.436 --> 05:51.829
Say hi, Dr. Ndugu!

05:51.873 --> 05:54.528
Hey. Do you mind not recording
so I can examine you?

05:54.571 --> 05:56.051
Oh, right, of course.

05:56.094 --> 05:59.010
Gotta go, y'all.
Kisses. [ Smooches ]

05:59.054 --> 06:01.273
Sorry. Gotta keep
my followers happy.

06:01.317 --> 06:02.579
I used to be
a travel influencer,

06:02.623 --> 06:03.580
ventured around the world,

06:03.624 --> 06:05.408
but now I'm DiabeticBae,

06:05.452 --> 06:08.411
which is way less exciting, so
I gotta get content where I can.

06:08.455 --> 06:11.240
Well, today won't be
too exciting, I'm afraid.

06:11.283 --> 06:12.937
I'll be inserting a catheter
into your chest

06:12.981 --> 06:14.635
to help you start dialysis.

06:14.678 --> 06:15.984
How long
have you been diabetic?

06:16.027 --> 06:18.029
Years now.
But I was able to manage it

06:18.073 --> 06:20.815
until I was visiting Thailand,
living my best life,

06:20.858 --> 06:22.251
and I got real sick.

06:22.294 --> 06:23.905
Hit my kidneys hard.

06:23.948 --> 06:25.950
And every time my doctors tried
to get access for dialysis,

06:25.994 --> 06:27.343
my body wouldn't cooperate

06:27.387 --> 06:30.259
because -- plot twist --
I have a clotting disorder.

06:30.302 --> 06:31.521
But none of this
was a shock.

06:31.565 --> 06:33.436
Both my mother and brother
were diabetic,

06:33.480 --> 06:35.569
and they both died
from kidney failure.

06:35.612 --> 06:36.918
Sorry to hear that.

06:36.961 --> 06:39.529
Were they able
to get kidney transplants?

06:39.573 --> 06:42.445
They weren't even able
to get on the list.

06:42.489 --> 06:43.620
And neither am I.

06:43.664 --> 06:45.143
You're not
on the transplant list?

06:45.187 --> 06:47.015
Nope.

06:47.058 --> 06:48.625
Ortiz, set me up a consult

06:48.669 --> 06:50.801
with Rashida's nephrologist,
Dr. Krause.

06:50.845 --> 06:52.455
Look, I know it's bad.

06:52.499 --> 06:54.022
But it's okay.

06:54.065 --> 06:56.764
That's really
why I record everything.

06:56.807 --> 06:58.461
I want the world
to know who I am

06:58.505 --> 07:01.551
before this disease...
ends me.

07:01.595 --> 07:03.292
♪♪

07:03.335 --> 07:05.076
[ Sirens wailing ]

07:05.120 --> 07:06.687
Hey.
Where's my resident?

07:06.730 --> 07:08.079
I'm not their keeper.

07:08.123 --> 07:09.603
What do we got?Paramedic: Noah Young, 35,

07:09.646 --> 07:11.126
auto vs. tree,
restrained driver,

07:11.169 --> 07:13.998
denies loss of consciousness,
O2 sats 89%,

07:14.042 --> 07:15.522
no visible chest trauma.Okay.

07:15.565 --> 07:17.306
Noah:
My son! I need to find my son!

07:17.349 --> 07:19.743
Okay. We got Danny Young, 7,
GCS 15,

07:19.787 --> 07:21.484
vital signs stable,
bleeding facial laceration.

07:21.528 --> 07:23.486
Daddy!There's my big guy!

07:23.530 --> 07:25.270
I need to see
my son, please!

07:25.314 --> 07:26.881
Okay. Let's get you
both inside first, okay?

07:26.924 --> 07:27.925
I'm fine!
I just need to --

07:27.969 --> 07:30.972
[ Coughing, wheezing ]

07:31.015 --> 07:33.670
Trauma one, let's get a chest
X-ray and a full trauma panel.

07:33.714 --> 07:35.933
Let's move!
Somebody find me a resident!

07:37.369 --> 07:40.285
Becoming a skilled surgeon
is like learning how to drive.

07:40.329 --> 07:42.070
The more you do it,
the better you become.

07:42.113 --> 07:44.551
And over the last year,
you have participated

07:44.594 --> 07:48.206
in fewer surgeries than any
class of surgeon ever has.

07:48.250 --> 07:50.121
Which means that you are not

07:50.165 --> 07:52.950
where you're supposed
to be, people.

07:52.994 --> 07:54.517
We woke up early
to be shamed.

07:54.561 --> 07:55.866
[ Groans ]

07:55.910 --> 07:57.912
Today, you will embark

07:57.955 --> 08:02.264
on the toughest surgical workout
you have ever experienced.

08:02.307 --> 08:06.224
Through a series of simulations
and skill assessments,

08:06.268 --> 08:10.359
each of you will be evaluated
in four areas --

08:10.402 --> 08:11.882
laparoscopic,

08:11.926 --> 08:14.102
suturing,
vascular skills,

08:14.145 --> 08:16.539
and endoscopic techniques.

08:16.583 --> 08:19.455
You will be graded
on your proficiency and speed,

08:19.499 --> 08:21.501
judged by your attendings.
Any questions?

08:21.544 --> 08:23.328
[ Whispering ]
It's like the surgical Olympics.

08:23.372 --> 08:25.200
Or the Hunger Games.

08:25.243 --> 08:27.594
I thought Dr. Grey was running
the residency program now.

08:27.637 --> 08:29.204
Who do you think
taught Dr. Grey?

08:29.247 --> 08:30.640
[ Residents chuckle ]Oh, and one more thing.

08:30.684 --> 08:32.903
The resident
with the highest score

08:32.947 --> 08:35.210
flies solo
in the OR this afternoon

08:35.253 --> 08:37.473
with a surgery that's
appropriate to their level.

08:37.517 --> 08:40.520
Laparoscopic skills start...now.

08:40.563 --> 08:41.738
Ah!

08:41.782 --> 08:44.567
♪♪

08:50.225 --> 08:53.097
Amelia: Relax your wrist for me.David: You know, back in my day,

08:53.141 --> 08:55.360
every neurosurgeon I worked with
was an egotistical prick.

08:55.404 --> 08:57.232
So you can imagine
my delight right now.

08:57.275 --> 09:00.714
You are brilliant
and charming, Dr. Shepherd.

09:00.757 --> 09:02.933
Oh, except when I'm being
an egotistical prick.

09:02.977 --> 09:04.544
[ Laughs ] Well,

09:04.587 --> 09:07.198
as my friend
Stephen Sondheim said,

09:07.242 --> 09:09.287
"Nice is different
than good."

09:09.331 --> 09:10.593
You're friends with
Stephen Sondheim?

09:10.637 --> 09:12.073
Oh, I could be.

09:12.116 --> 09:13.465
Amelia:
Okay. Follow my movements.

09:18.645 --> 09:21.865
So, Dr. Shepherd, what's your
golden opinion? How do I look?

09:21.909 --> 09:23.693
Well, you only have
a mild resting tremor

09:23.737 --> 09:25.216
and slight bradykinesia,
which is good,

09:25.260 --> 09:26.914
but Parkinson's
is unpredictable.

09:26.957 --> 09:29.917
Your dopaminergic neurons
are degenerating gradually,

09:29.960 --> 09:31.875
and it's only
a matter of time.

09:31.919 --> 09:33.442
Have you considered
switching your meds

09:33.485 --> 09:34.617
or deep-brain stimulation?

09:34.661 --> 09:36.314
You know,

09:36.358 --> 09:38.186
I'm not interested
in a Band-Aid.

09:38.229 --> 09:40.492
I need something
that'll make me whole again.

09:40.536 --> 09:42.625
Dr. Hamilton,

09:42.669 --> 09:45.585
Parkinson's is not a condition
that surgery can fix.

09:45.628 --> 09:49.197
Yet. A condition
that surgery can't fix yet.

09:49.240 --> 09:53.027
Enter brilliant, charming,
egotistical you.

09:53.070 --> 09:55.682
As long as we can convince
your sister-in-law over here.

09:55.725 --> 09:59.642
♪♪

09:59.686 --> 10:01.165
Chest pain, no.

10:01.209 --> 10:04.429
Open fracture, too specialized.

10:04.473 --> 10:07.563
Oh, right upper quadrant pain --
now, that's promising.

10:07.607 --> 10:09.043
Dr. Bailey.

10:09.086 --> 10:10.653
Wong.

10:10.697 --> 10:13.438
Uh, Richard's holding
the surgical Olympics.

10:13.482 --> 10:16.180
It's a slow day, so I'm looking
for something good

10:16.224 --> 10:17.878
to be the solo.
You got anything?

10:17.921 --> 10:21.185
Dr. Bailey, you've rescheduled
our meeting twice now.

10:21.229 --> 10:22.709
You're avoiding me.No --

10:22.752 --> 10:25.537
I had surgeries.
Uh, important ones.

10:25.581 --> 10:26.887
He's also
looking for judges,

10:26.930 --> 10:29.106
so if you'd prefer
to help out that way...

10:29.150 --> 10:31.761
No, I'm here
to tender my resignation,

10:31.805 --> 10:33.328
which I've been trying to do
for days now.
[ Sighs ]

10:33.371 --> 10:35.635
I know.
I just didn't want you to.

10:35.678 --> 10:37.462
Chief, I'm retiring.

10:37.506 --> 10:39.682
I already bought a condo,
picked out tile.

10:39.726 --> 10:43.338
Okay, what could you possibly
want to do instead of surgery?

10:43.381 --> 10:44.687
Mystery novels.

10:44.731 --> 10:46.384
I'm sorry?I have a series of books

10:46.428 --> 10:49.823
where the main character is a PI
and a surgeon.

10:49.866 --> 10:51.389
"Doc Undercover."

10:51.433 --> 10:52.782
[ Laughs ]

10:52.826 --> 10:56.438
Uh, sounds...n-nice.

10:56.481 --> 10:59.093
Wong, look, the hospital,
t-the country --

10:59.136 --> 11:01.008
we're in dire need
of physicians with yo--

11:01.051 --> 11:03.140
Miranda.

11:03.184 --> 11:06.491
Truthfully?
It's just not fun anymore.

11:06.535 --> 11:08.537
I'll start your paperwork.

11:08.580 --> 11:14.195
♪♪

11:14.238 --> 11:17.502
Perfect suturing ensures
proper wound closure,

11:17.546 --> 11:19.156
less bleeding,

11:19.200 --> 11:21.376
and a lower risk
of infection.

11:21.419 --> 11:23.334
Excellence matters.

11:23.378 --> 11:25.510
This is an atraumatic tie.

11:25.554 --> 11:28.731
You will have 20 seconds
to tie three square knots.

11:28.775 --> 11:32.387
Do not move the soda can.
Any movement counts against you.

11:32.430 --> 11:35.346
And absolutely no air knots.

11:35.390 --> 11:38.610
On your mark, set...

11:38.654 --> 11:40.221
Go![ Stopwatch clicks ]

11:40.264 --> 11:42.876
♪ Call me cynical,
but original ♪

11:42.919 --> 11:45.748
♪ Tryin' to fit into a world
that's so digital ♪

11:45.792 --> 11:48.229
♪ Came to let you know
I left the pigeon hole ♪

11:48.272 --> 11:49.709
Kinda sloppy, Tseng.

11:49.752 --> 11:50.884
♪ Now I gotta find an edge,
won't let it go ♪

11:50.927 --> 11:53.408
♪ I know my mind

11:53.451 --> 11:55.149
♪ This could be our time

11:55.192 --> 11:56.759
Huh.What's that supposed to mean?

11:56.803 --> 11:59.762
It means, "Huh."

11:59.806 --> 12:01.895
Is that better?
Nope.

12:01.938 --> 12:04.332
♪ All I need

12:04.375 --> 12:07.074
♪ It don't let me down,
it don't let me down ♪

12:07.117 --> 12:09.424
I'd start over
if I were you.

12:09.467 --> 12:11.600
Opening with a compliment
is customary.

12:11.643 --> 12:13.123
[ Stopwatch clicks ]Time's up!

12:13.167 --> 12:15.865
Lincoln,
do we have a winner?

12:15.909 --> 12:18.085
Schmitt takes the gold.Yes!

12:18.128 --> 12:19.608
[ Grunts ]Is there a silver?

12:19.651 --> 12:22.785
♪♪

12:22.829 --> 12:25.440
[ Whistling "Twinkle, Twinkle,
Little Star" ]

12:29.052 --> 12:30.314
Name that tune.

12:30.358 --> 12:31.794
[ Continues whistling ]I don't know.

12:31.838 --> 12:34.144
Um, how long did you say

12:34.188 --> 12:37.800
that you have been experiencing
abdominal pain for?

12:37.844 --> 12:39.759
Uh, a few days.
Okay.

12:39.802 --> 12:41.064
Whistling calms my nerves

12:41.108 --> 12:43.501
when someone's, you know,
inspecting my hooha.

12:43.545 --> 12:46.417
[ Chuckles,
continues whistling ]

12:46.461 --> 12:47.462
Ow.

12:47.505 --> 12:50.770
Sorry, but I-I
feel something.

12:52.467 --> 12:54.208
It was "Twinkle, Twinkle,
Little Star." [ Chuckles ]

12:54.251 --> 12:55.949
What?The song I was whistling.

12:55.992 --> 12:57.602
"Twinkle, Twinkle"?

12:57.646 --> 13:00.692
Oh.
Technically, it's the same
melody as the ABCs.

13:00.736 --> 13:01.563
And "Baa Baa Black Sheep."

13:01.606 --> 13:02.956
Ah. Who knew.

13:02.999 --> 13:04.827
Okay, I --

13:04.871 --> 13:07.395
Yep, there's
something in here --

13:07.438 --> 13:08.962
I --

13:09.005 --> 13:11.399
♪♪

13:11.442 --> 13:16.491
Robin, there was a strawberry
lodged in your --

13:16.534 --> 13:18.623
Ohhhh.

13:18.667 --> 13:20.625
Yep. That tracks.

13:20.669 --> 13:23.237
So would that explain
my abdominal pain?

13:23.280 --> 13:25.369
Um, it shouldn't.

13:25.413 --> 13:27.719
Why?
Is there something...

13:27.763 --> 13:30.287
strange in there, too?
[ Chuckles ]

13:30.331 --> 13:31.549
Maybe?

13:31.593 --> 13:34.552
♪♪

13:34.596 --> 13:36.728
Danny.[ Woman speaking indistinctly
over P.A.]

13:36.772 --> 13:37.860
How you feeling?

13:37.904 --> 13:39.340
Looks like you had
quite the adventure.

13:39.383 --> 13:40.471
Yeah.

13:40.515 --> 13:41.864
Got to ride
in an ambulance.

13:41.908 --> 13:43.997
And now you have
superhero marks.

13:44.040 --> 13:45.737
Do they come with powers?

13:45.781 --> 13:48.740
Maybe, if you eat enough
cherry Jell-O and popsicles.

13:48.784 --> 13:50.830
Owen's sister, right?

13:50.873 --> 13:52.614
Oh, uh, yeah.
You're peds?

13:52.657 --> 13:53.920
Cormac Hayes.Oh.

13:53.963 --> 13:55.486
You coming to join
our humble staff?

13:55.530 --> 13:56.879
[ Chuckles ]

13:56.923 --> 13:58.315
Bailey just asked me
to help out,

13:58.359 --> 13:59.795
cover some of Grey's cases.

13:59.839 --> 14:01.318
Grey?
Big shoes to fill.

14:01.362 --> 14:03.843
Eh. So she performed
an abdominal-wall transplant.

14:03.886 --> 14:05.888
Big whoop.
It was actually my idea

14:05.932 --> 14:08.021
to even need
an entirely new abdominal wall

14:08.064 --> 14:10.588
so Grey could win the Fox award,
so, who's the genius now?

14:10.632 --> 14:12.286
So you were the patient?Yep.

14:12.329 --> 14:15.028
Alright, Danny, I'll be back
to check on you, okay?

14:16.377 --> 14:18.727
Where's my dad?

14:18.770 --> 14:20.511
Can I please go sit
with him?

14:20.555 --> 14:22.209
He shouldn't be alone
out there.

14:22.252 --> 14:25.429
We have contacted your wife,
and she is on her way, okay?

14:25.473 --> 14:27.127
It was supposed to be
a father-and-son weekend.

14:27.170 --> 14:28.824
Fishing, camping
out by Deception Bay.

14:28.868 --> 14:30.652
I don't know what happened.Maybe you passed out.

14:30.695 --> 14:32.262
Your oxygen levels
are very low.

14:32.306 --> 14:33.568
How long have you had
shortness of breath?

14:33.611 --> 14:35.483
It -- It's nothing.

14:35.526 --> 14:36.788
Okay, let's do
an X-ray, please?

14:36.832 --> 14:38.225
No! No X-ray!Hey.

14:38.268 --> 14:40.009
Look, I'm fine.

14:40.053 --> 14:41.750
Relieved that me and Danny
are alive.

14:41.793 --> 14:42.925
Could you please
let me out of here

14:42.969 --> 14:44.274
so I can try to salvage
this weeken--

14:44.318 --> 14:45.972
[ Coughing ]

14:48.191 --> 14:51.325
I, uh -- I saw your tattoo.
Bassett Infantry?

14:51.368 --> 14:53.022
3rd generation,
Bassett Infantry.Mm.

14:53.066 --> 14:54.110
You?

14:54.154 --> 14:55.633
Army trauma surgeon,
two tours Iraq.

14:55.677 --> 14:57.070
Two tours Afghanistan,

14:57.113 --> 15:00.334
one Jordan, one Djibouti,
two Iraq.

15:00.377 --> 15:01.944
And I've never
been to Vancouver.

15:01.988 --> 15:03.641
Well, sounds like
you need a new travel agent.

15:03.685 --> 15:06.340
[ Laughs, coughs ]

15:06.383 --> 15:08.864
[ Coughing ]

15:08.908 --> 15:10.431
[ Retching ]

15:10.474 --> 15:11.911
Let's put him
on high-flow O2.

15:11.954 --> 15:14.304
Let's push 50 of fentanyl,
and somebody page Altman!

15:14.348 --> 15:16.002
We're gonna
get him up to CT!

15:16.045 --> 15:17.394
Okay?

15:17.438 --> 15:19.657
[ Continues coughing ]

15:19.701 --> 15:21.572
Okay.[ Gasps ]

15:21.616 --> 15:23.531
Dr. Krause, hi.

15:23.574 --> 15:25.489
Winston Ndugu,
cardiothoracic surgery.

15:25.533 --> 15:27.013
Do you have a minute?Barely.

15:27.056 --> 15:28.362
I've been drowning
in cases.

15:28.405 --> 15:29.972
My patients put off
seeing me for months,

15:30.016 --> 15:31.365
and now I'm dealing
with the backlog.

15:31.408 --> 15:32.975
What can I do for you?Yeah, I'm consulting

15:33.019 --> 15:34.672
on your patient
Rashida Flowers.

15:34.716 --> 15:36.544
She mentioned that she's not
on the transplant list.

15:36.587 --> 15:38.372
Yeah. Rashida,
she's been through a lot.

15:38.415 --> 15:40.896
Unfortunately, she doesn't fit
the transplant criteria.

15:40.940 --> 15:42.419
But Rashida's
renal function tests

15:42.463 --> 15:44.247
seem to make her
a prime candidate.

15:44.291 --> 15:46.380
Well, you would think,
but Rashida's eGFR is high.

15:46.423 --> 15:48.382
It's over 20, disqualifying her
from the list.

15:48.425 --> 15:49.992
Estimated.I'm sorry?

15:50.036 --> 15:51.951
It's an estimated number of what
her kidney function should be,

15:51.994 --> 15:53.561
not what it really is.Dr. Ndugu,

15:53.604 --> 15:56.346
the eGFR is the standard
clinical formula,

15:56.390 --> 15:58.566
used in the field
for the past 20 years.

15:58.609 --> 16:00.742
It's what we use to determine
care and qualification

16:00.785 --> 16:02.222
of kidney transplant.

16:02.265 --> 16:04.224
A transplant could save her
from having to need dialysis

16:04.267 --> 16:05.703
in the first place,
which we both know

16:05.747 --> 16:07.009
has high mortality rates,

16:07.053 --> 16:08.271
especially in
the first three months.

16:08.315 --> 16:10.534
I'm aware, but Rashida
just doesn't qualify.

16:10.578 --> 16:12.623
And believe me,
I hate that,

16:12.667 --> 16:14.495
at least as much
as you do.

16:14.538 --> 16:20.022
♪♪

16:21.502 --> 16:23.721
Meredith:
So, what if we fail?

16:23.765 --> 16:25.114
How do we know
you'll even survive it?

16:25.158 --> 16:26.550
I think we can both agree

16:26.594 --> 16:30.337
that you learn more
in the attempt than the outcome.

16:30.380 --> 16:34.776
And I am under no delusion
about how risky it is.

16:34.819 --> 16:36.386
But what's life
without risk?

16:36.430 --> 16:38.040
Amelia: Meredith?

16:38.084 --> 16:39.650
Meredith.

16:39.694 --> 16:41.174
[ Chuckles ]

16:41.217 --> 16:43.219
Is this that robot arm
that does cell culture?

16:43.263 --> 16:45.874
Dr. Bartley: It is.
And please don't touch it.

16:45.917 --> 16:48.659
Dr. Grey, Dr. Shepherd,
please meet Dr. Kai Bartley,

16:48.703 --> 16:51.836
a neuroscientist who accepted
an offer they couldn't refuse.

16:51.880 --> 16:53.055
Meredith:
It's great to meet you.

16:53.099 --> 16:54.752
I've been reading
your stem cell research.

16:54.796 --> 16:56.145
Which is brilliant.

16:56.189 --> 16:57.799
I've been following it
for years.

16:57.842 --> 17:00.541
Um, they were at Hopkins
a couple years behind me.

17:00.584 --> 17:03.761
Um, o-okay. When you inject
the cells into the brain,

17:03.805 --> 17:05.937
what about the risk of the cells
developing tumors?

17:05.981 --> 17:08.549
That very question stalled
my research for two years.

17:08.592 --> 17:09.811
But once I teamed up
with David --

17:09.854 --> 17:11.508
Once they took my funding.

17:11.552 --> 17:13.597
I uncovered
a Chinese herbal compound

17:13.641 --> 17:16.557
that completely removes
the undifferentiated cells.

17:16.600 --> 17:18.515
That's amazing.
They're amazing.

17:18.559 --> 17:19.603
Excuse me,
I have a conference call.

17:19.647 --> 17:21.040
But we'll talk more later?

17:21.083 --> 17:22.432
Meredith: Great to meet you.Thank you, Dr. Bartley.

17:22.476 --> 17:23.912
Thank you, David.

17:23.955 --> 17:25.522
So?

17:25.566 --> 17:26.784
What do you --

17:26.828 --> 17:28.395
Yes.
All the yeses.

17:28.438 --> 17:31.137
An opportunity to impact
Parkinson's, change the world,

17:31.180 --> 17:32.573
with this equipment
and this team?

17:32.616 --> 17:35.054
I am -- I'm in.

17:35.097 --> 17:36.577
Dr. Grey?

17:36.620 --> 17:38.361
Just say yes.

17:38.405 --> 17:40.146
♪♪

17:46.674 --> 17:48.110
[ Machine whirring ]

17:48.154 --> 17:49.198
Teddy: Hey.

17:51.113 --> 17:53.420
Should we shelve
the Elsa costume?

17:53.463 --> 17:56.031
What?You know, put Leo in more...

17:56.075 --> 17:58.164
T-shirts and jeans?

17:58.207 --> 18:00.514
Just, is that the right
parenting move?

18:00.557 --> 18:02.211
Did something happen?No, I just --

18:02.255 --> 18:04.039
You know, none
of the other kids at daycare

18:04.083 --> 18:07.347
are wearing costumes,
so I just...

18:07.390 --> 18:09.436
What do we got?MVC with no visible trauma.

18:09.479 --> 18:11.916
A young vet
who did several tours in Iraq.

18:11.960 --> 18:14.223
He has finger clubbing,
cyanosis, dyspnea.

18:14.267 --> 18:16.182
He coughed up blood
when he was downstairs.

18:16.225 --> 18:17.792
His chest X-ray
does not look good.

18:17.835 --> 18:21.056
And I'm thinking it's some kind
of respiratory illness.

18:21.100 --> 18:22.666
Are you sure
nothing happened?

18:22.710 --> 18:24.755
♪♪

18:24.799 --> 18:27.497
Oh, my God. Owen...

18:27.541 --> 18:28.977
[ Sighs ]

18:29.020 --> 18:31.110
His lungs
look like a war zone.

18:31.153 --> 18:34.417
♪♪

18:34.461 --> 18:36.027
Is Pierce taking a job
in Boston?

18:36.071 --> 18:37.159
Is that why you paged me?

18:37.203 --> 18:39.161
Because if I lose
one more surgeon --

18:39.205 --> 18:40.989
No, her dad
is having hip surgery.

18:41.032 --> 18:42.425
Oh.

18:42.469 --> 18:44.079
Well, now I feel badly.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.037
Uh, Chief,
I have a patient, 34,

18:46.081 --> 18:48.301
Black woman with chronic kidney
disease from diabetes.

18:48.344 --> 18:49.737
She hasn't been able
to get on dialysis

18:49.780 --> 18:51.130
due to
a clotting disorder.

18:51.173 --> 18:52.261
A candidate
for transplant?

18:52.305 --> 18:54.220
Well, her eGFR
is too high,

18:54.263 --> 18:55.830
according to
her nephrologist.

18:55.873 --> 18:57.440
But look.

18:57.484 --> 18:59.268
Here's another patient
on the transplant list.

18:59.312 --> 19:02.576
Almost the same age, weight, and
health profile to my patient.

19:02.619 --> 19:05.796
The only real differentiating
factor is that they're white.

19:05.840 --> 19:07.581
Sara:
So their eGFR measures lower,

19:07.624 --> 19:10.236
making them
better transplant candidates.

19:10.279 --> 19:12.412
When the estimated GFR
was developed,

19:12.455 --> 19:15.893
it was assumed that Black people
have higher muscle mass.

19:15.937 --> 19:17.939
It added a multiplier
to account for that assumption,

19:17.982 --> 19:20.202
which then increases
a Black patient's GFR

19:20.246 --> 19:22.117
and registers them
as having less severe disease

19:22.161 --> 19:23.292
than other people.

19:23.336 --> 19:25.686
Making them ineligible
for transplants.

19:25.729 --> 19:26.817
How does this
even happen?

19:26.861 --> 19:28.341
Stems from a long line

19:28.384 --> 19:30.256
of "assumptions"
about Black people

19:30.299 --> 19:32.606
that have snaked their way
into medicine --

19:32.649 --> 19:35.696
you know, that we have
a higher tolerance for pain...Ah.

19:35.739 --> 19:38.394
...different bone density,
lower lung capacity.

19:38.438 --> 19:42.442
And yet these assumptions still
exist in clinical formulas.

19:42.485 --> 19:46.837
I-I never even stopped to think
about the eGFR.

19:46.881 --> 19:48.883
Is there any way
around it, Chief?

19:48.926 --> 19:50.841
Uh, can I write an appeal
to the transplant board?

19:50.885 --> 19:52.278
That only works

19:52.321 --> 19:55.585
if the patient qualifies
for medically urgent status.

19:55.629 --> 19:57.979
Rashida might not have
that kind of time.

19:58.022 --> 20:00.373
There's a lot
of Rashidas, though.

20:00.416 --> 20:02.549
♪♪

20:02.592 --> 20:05.421
Fight for them, too.

20:05.465 --> 20:07.815
[ Cellphone vibrates ]

20:07.858 --> 20:09.773
The IR suite
is ready for us.

20:09.817 --> 20:13.560
♪♪

20:13.603 --> 20:15.866
Sergeant Young,
this is Dr. Teddy Altman.

20:15.910 --> 20:17.216
MajorTeddy Altman.

20:17.259 --> 20:19.305
Where's Danny?He's with Dr. Hayes.

20:19.348 --> 20:21.524
He's fine, but we need to do
a head CT just to be sure.

20:21.568 --> 20:24.005
Teddy: Your scans reveal severe
scarring in both your lungs.

20:24.048 --> 20:25.267
We'd like
to admit you and --

20:25.311 --> 20:27.965
I have pulmonary fibrosis.

20:28.009 --> 20:29.489
Mystery solved.

20:29.532 --> 20:32.622
That's why I didn't want
any work-ups, no treatments.

20:32.666 --> 20:34.537
I know what I have,
and I know there's no cure.

20:34.581 --> 20:36.496
Just a crap-ton of different
ways to the poor house.

20:36.539 --> 20:38.193
When were you diagnosed,
Sergeant?

20:38.237 --> 20:39.542
About a year ago.

20:39.586 --> 20:41.762
I started coughing
after the second Iraq tour.

20:41.805 --> 20:43.198
I couldn't shake it.

20:43.242 --> 20:46.680
I started hearing from buddies
about the burn pits,

20:46.723 --> 20:49.770
how they were linked
to all these cancers

20:49.813 --> 20:51.075
and mystery illnesses.

20:51.119 --> 20:52.947
The VA's gotta cover
these conditions.

20:52.990 --> 20:54.296
[ Chuckles, coughs ]

20:54.340 --> 20:55.645
Barely.

20:55.689 --> 20:57.560
They just started covering
stuff like asthma.

20:57.604 --> 20:59.214
But I haven't heard
of a single vet

20:59.258 --> 21:00.781
who's been covered
for conditions like mine.

21:00.824 --> 21:02.783
All kinds of ways to twist it

21:02.826 --> 21:05.002
so you can't prove
it was service-related.

21:05.046 --> 21:07.309
Cherry on top? I lost my job
at the seafood plant

21:07.353 --> 21:09.746
'cause I was too weak
to finish my shift.

21:09.790 --> 21:13.533
So I got no insurance, no job,
and a stack of medical bills.

21:13.576 --> 21:15.622
Sergeant, look --Please, just call me Noah.

21:15.665 --> 21:18.102
Noah, would you sit down
with one of our pulmonologists?

21:18.146 --> 21:21.149
We'll redo your workup, and we
will get you in for some tests

21:21.192 --> 21:22.759
so that we can start
some treatments --

21:22.803 --> 21:25.414
Pass.
No tests, no treatments.

21:25.458 --> 21:28.852
Nothing against you guys,
but whatever time I have left,

21:28.896 --> 21:30.724
I'd like to spend it
with my son.

21:32.378 --> 21:34.510
-Move. That's four.
-I know, I know, I know!

21:34.554 --> 21:35.990
Pop these balloons, Tseng!
Come on!

21:36.033 --> 21:37.861
If you lose to a second-year,

21:37.905 --> 21:39.385
you're cleaning the bathroom
for six months!

21:39.428 --> 21:41.387
Get away from me!Hayes: Endoscopic proficiency

21:41.430 --> 21:43.084
is just as important
as speed.

21:43.127 --> 21:45.304
One slip could mean
you've perforated a colon.

21:45.347 --> 21:46.392
20 seconds!

21:46.435 --> 21:48.829
-Yes, yes, yes!
-One more.

21:48.872 --> 21:50.221
What category
are they on?

21:50.265 --> 21:51.614
Endoscopy.
Mm.

21:51.658 --> 21:52.833
It's a trash fire.

21:52.876 --> 21:54.138
Mnh-mnh.You're a resident now.

21:54.182 --> 21:55.401
Sleep when you can,
eat when you can.

21:55.444 --> 21:57.359
Nah, I'm on the scut diet.

21:57.403 --> 21:58.447
Rectal exams?

21:58.491 --> 21:59.666
Vaginas.

21:59.709 --> 22:01.189
Right. Pink.

22:01.232 --> 22:02.233
[ Residents shouting
indistinctly ]

22:02.277 --> 22:03.322
The scrubs!

22:03.365 --> 22:04.932
[ Laughs ]

22:04.975 --> 22:07.195
I found a strawberry
in my patient.

22:07.238 --> 22:08.936
[ Laughs ]
Back in med school,

22:08.979 --> 22:11.199
I found a yam.
20 bucks on Tseng.

22:11.242 --> 22:12.766
Okay, I'll take Helm.Come on, come on, come on!

22:12.809 --> 22:14.333
Go, go!
Taryn, it's right there,

22:14.376 --> 22:15.508
it's right there,
it's right there!

22:15.551 --> 22:16.813
Go, go, go!
Come on, come on, come on!

22:16.857 --> 22:18.859
Go, go.[ All cheering ]

22:18.902 --> 22:20.034
[ All shouting indistinctly ]

22:20.077 --> 22:22.428
-Done!
-Finished, finished. Me.

22:22.471 --> 22:23.429
It's Tseng.

22:23.472 --> 22:25.866
[ All cheering ]

22:25.909 --> 22:28.608
[ Tseng laughs, sighs ]

22:28.651 --> 22:31.001
Today's winner
of the competition...

22:35.049 --> 22:37.878
Schmitt, you will be
flying solo today.

22:37.921 --> 22:39.749
I won.
I won, I won!

22:39.793 --> 22:41.708
I won! Oh!

22:41.751 --> 22:43.579
Of course he won.
There was no actual blood.

22:43.623 --> 22:45.407
Oh, come on! Wait, wait.
What's the -- What's the --

22:45.451 --> 22:47.148
What's the surgery?

22:47.191 --> 22:48.932
Find anything good?Wilson did.

22:48.976 --> 22:52.414
[ Clears throat ] Ex-lap
on foreign-body extraction.

22:52.458 --> 22:53.894
Yes! Oww!

22:53.937 --> 22:55.025
Get it, get it!

22:55.069 --> 22:56.331
Oww!

22:56.375 --> 22:58.594
Yes!

22:58.638 --> 22:59.900
I love you!

22:59.943 --> 23:01.205
[ Laughs, claps hands ]

23:02.816 --> 23:05.166
Amelia:
Hmm, let's think.

23:05.209 --> 23:09.170
Deep pockets,
unlimited time, space,

23:09.213 --> 23:10.824
Kai Bartley's
groundbreaking research,

23:10.867 --> 23:13.217
and a chance at curing
a neurodegenerative disease.

23:13.261 --> 23:14.436
You're forgetting
about the part

23:14.480 --> 23:17.091
where we have kids
who need stability.

23:17.134 --> 23:19.528
And I have a job that I love
that I just got back to.

23:19.572 --> 23:20.834
I don't want
to abandon them.

23:20.877 --> 23:22.444
We're not
abandoning anyone.

23:22.488 --> 23:24.446
We're revolutionizing
medicine,

23:24.490 --> 23:27.318
and that's a great example
to set for our kids.

23:27.362 --> 23:30.017
And Grey-Sloan,
they're gonna be proud

23:30.060 --> 23:32.149
to have us be part
of something so high-profile.

23:32.193 --> 23:35.283
Exactly. If this surgery works,
it's huge.

23:35.326 --> 23:38.286
If it doesn't, we've killed
an incredible surgeon

23:38.329 --> 23:40.462
and set the research
back years.

23:40.506 --> 23:42.116
Give us more credit than that,
Meredith.

23:42.159 --> 23:43.683
You asked me here
for my opinion.

23:43.726 --> 23:45.772
I'm saying yes.

23:45.815 --> 23:50.211
Because people with Parkinson's
need more than just hope.

23:50.254 --> 23:53.823
♪♪

23:53.867 --> 23:56.565
[ Monitor beeping ]

23:56.609 --> 23:59.481
Sara: Is this her last possible
access port for dialysis?

23:59.525 --> 24:02.310
Winston: It is. We need to pull
back the catheter just a bit.

24:02.353 --> 24:04.704
What about transhepatic
or translumbar access?

24:04.747 --> 24:06.836
It'd be too dangerous,
given her clotting disorder.

24:06.880 --> 24:09.143
Fluoro. This isn't
how medicine should work.

24:09.186 --> 24:11.406
Anybody who needs life-saving
care should get it.

24:11.450 --> 24:12.668
Heparinized saline.

24:14.148 --> 24:16.237
What if this port clots off
and she loses it?

24:16.280 --> 24:17.804
You tell me.

24:17.847 --> 24:20.589
Waste will build up
in her blood, leading to uremia,

24:20.633 --> 24:23.418
and her organs will start to
shut down, one after the other.

24:23.462 --> 24:27.378
♪♪

24:27.422 --> 24:29.250
Secure the catheter with
stitches on the wings and shaft.

24:29.293 --> 24:30.512
Get a chest X-ray.

24:31.774 --> 24:33.515
Where are you going?

24:33.559 --> 24:34.951
To get her a kidney.

24:42.350 --> 24:44.265
You don't need to escort me
off the premises.

24:44.308 --> 24:46.180
[ Chuckles ]
That's not what I'm doing.

24:46.223 --> 24:47.573
Go home to your baby.[ Vehicle door opens ]

24:47.616 --> 24:48.791
I just wanted
to make sure that

24:48.835 --> 24:50.489
I'm not being
completely ridiculous

24:50.532 --> 24:52.447
for even
entertaining this.

24:52.491 --> 24:53.796
No, you're
being ridiculous

24:53.840 --> 24:55.842
because you haven't
accepted the offer yet.

24:55.885 --> 24:58.584
I mean, we're talking about
curing Parkinson's, Meredith.

24:58.627 --> 25:00.542
Parkinson's. I mean,
what is the matter with you?

25:00.586 --> 25:04.415
This -- This famous surgeon is
basically throwing money at us

25:04.459 --> 25:08.463
to play with the most innovative
equipment in the world.

25:08.507 --> 25:10.770
And not only that, he wants
to give us his diseased brain

25:10.813 --> 25:12.206
as a testing ground!

25:12.249 --> 25:14.121
I mean, when you
started your career,

25:14.164 --> 25:15.470
you wanted
to go into neuro.

25:15.514 --> 25:17.733
This is your chance
to get back to that.

25:17.777 --> 25:20.301
I mean, maybe this is what
you're supposed to do.

25:20.344 --> 25:21.650
What we're supposed to do.

25:21.694 --> 25:25.219
And I-I -- I cannot,
for the life of me, understand

25:25.262 --> 25:27.351
why you would walk away
from something like this. I --

25:27.395 --> 25:29.919
[ Sighs ]

25:29.963 --> 25:31.312
So don't.

25:31.355 --> 25:33.444
♪♪

25:33.488 --> 25:35.055
I will see you
at home.

25:35.098 --> 25:43.019
♪♪

25:43.063 --> 25:44.630
I inserted
Rashida's access point.

25:44.673 --> 25:46.545
Great. Thanks.

25:46.588 --> 25:48.590
Rashida needs to be
on the transplant list.

25:48.634 --> 25:50.897
We found six cases of patients
with similar clinical profiles,

25:50.940 --> 25:52.551
who are on the list.

25:52.594 --> 25:54.204
The only major difference is
that these patients are white.

25:54.248 --> 25:55.554
Are those cases
patients of mine?

25:55.597 --> 25:57.120
A few.
[ Scoffs ]

25:57.164 --> 25:59.383
There's got to be more to it
than that. The patients' eGFR --

25:59.427 --> 26:01.385
Yeah, their eGFR is lower,
which makes them eligible,

26:01.429 --> 26:02.778
but that's only because

26:02.822 --> 26:04.867
the formula unjustifiably
uses race as a factor.

26:04.911 --> 26:06.303
Dr. Krause, we all know

26:06.347 --> 26:07.783
race doesn't play a role
in kidney function.

26:07.827 --> 26:09.176
Dr. Ndugu --I know, you're busy,

26:09.219 --> 26:11.004
but if you look
at Rashida's eGFR

26:11.047 --> 26:12.440
without accounting
for her race,

26:12.483 --> 26:14.877
she falls below
the criterion of 20.

26:14.921 --> 26:17.837
I don't understand. The eGFR
is the field's standard.

26:17.880 --> 26:19.969
It's a tried
and true formula.

26:20.013 --> 26:23.233
Yes. And it's time we start
questioning our standards.[ Elevator bell dings ]

26:23.277 --> 26:25.453
Look, I have clinic right now,
but I'll look into it.

26:25.496 --> 26:27.629
Rashida doesn't have other
options for a dialysis port

26:27.673 --> 26:29.022
if this one fails.I hear you.

26:29.065 --> 26:31.502
I'll look into it,
Dr. Ndugu. Thank you.

26:31.546 --> 26:34.331
♪♪

26:34.375 --> 26:36.725
Robin Jeter, 23,
abdominal pain.

26:36.769 --> 26:40.033
X-ray shows a lodged crystal
causing intestinal obstruction.

26:40.076 --> 26:42.818
I think you mean to say
intestinal stone.

26:42.862 --> 26:44.385
No, I don't.No, she didn't.

26:44.428 --> 26:45.778
Robin:
It's a yoni egg.

26:45.821 --> 26:48.084
Amethyst, specifically.Uh --

26:48.128 --> 26:49.825
It's -- It's --
It's a crystal egg

26:49.869 --> 26:52.611
that is typically inserted
into the vagin--

26:52.654 --> 26:54.134
Got it.
Huh?

26:54.177 --> 26:57.224
Uh, I was doing a ritual
I saw on social media

26:57.267 --> 27:00.140
that was supposed to bring love
and healing into your life.

27:00.183 --> 27:02.795
But, um, I was doing it so fast,
I mixed it all up.

27:02.838 --> 27:04.492
I was supposed
to eatthe strawberry

27:04.535 --> 27:06.625
and insertthe yoni egg.

27:06.668 --> 27:08.888
What did you do
with the strawberry?

27:11.020 --> 27:14.720
Oh. Uh, I-I see. Um.

27:14.763 --> 27:16.199
[ Clears throat ]

27:16.243 --> 27:18.854
Oh! Right. I'm up.

27:18.898 --> 27:20.377
Hello, Robin.
I'm Dr. Schmitt.

27:20.421 --> 27:23.990
I'll be doing your surgery
today, uh, to remove,

27:24.033 --> 27:25.687
uh, the...

27:25.731 --> 27:26.470
The --Yoni egg.

27:26.514 --> 27:28.647
Mm-hmm.

27:28.690 --> 27:30.126
How old is he?

27:31.911 --> 27:33.826
Megan: Yeah,
these symptoms sound familiar.

27:33.869 --> 27:36.437
I have treated dozens of
soldiers exposed to burn pits.

27:36.480 --> 27:38.265
What are burn pits?

27:38.308 --> 27:42.399
Electronics, plastics,
soiled uniforms, human waste.

27:42.443 --> 27:44.445
Douse it all with some jet fuel,
light it with a match,

27:44.488 --> 27:47.187
then fwoosh -- I mean,
what could possibly go wrong?

27:47.230 --> 27:48.797
I mean, some
of these men have illnesses

27:48.841 --> 27:49.885
that we haven't
even named yet.

27:49.929 --> 27:51.713
Others are in pain 24/7.

27:51.757 --> 27:53.193
They get nowhere
with the VA.

27:53.236 --> 27:54.585
Owen: The guy did
six tours of service.

27:54.629 --> 27:56.457
To protect us.

27:56.500 --> 27:57.763
Never questioning,
never complaining.

27:57.806 --> 27:59.329
He just answered the call,

27:59.373 --> 28:00.722
and we need to do
the same for him.

28:00.766 --> 28:01.810
Tomorrow, I'm gonna
go down to the VA.

28:01.854 --> 28:03.159
I'm gonna demand answers.

28:03.203 --> 28:05.684
Okay, so after you defeat
the US military,

28:05.727 --> 28:08.512
maybe grab some lunch,
and then take on Putin?[ Chuckles ]

28:08.556 --> 28:10.210
How's his kid?Danny's gonna be fine.

28:10.253 --> 28:13.387
Head CT was clear. He can be
discharged later today.

28:13.430 --> 28:16.216
Maybe Avery can help Noah
through the foundation.

28:16.259 --> 28:18.740
He'll be dead before we even
line up the votes on the board.

28:18.784 --> 28:20.524
We can't save Noah.

28:20.568 --> 28:22.831
He just needs immediate medical
care just to be comfortable.

28:22.875 --> 28:25.747
And we can give him that. We'll
figure out the details later.

28:25.791 --> 28:28.228
Look at you two,
breaking rules and saving lives.

28:28.271 --> 28:30.404
Aren't you glad
I got you to tie that knot?

28:30.447 --> 28:32.406
♪♪

28:32.449 --> 28:34.930
[ Danny speaking
indistinctly ]

28:34.974 --> 28:37.454
♪♪

28:37.498 --> 28:38.673
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

28:38.717 --> 28:40.457
Winston: What happened?Her sats dropped,

28:40.501 --> 28:43.156
and her face and neck keep
swelling more and more.

28:43.199 --> 28:45.419
Superior vena cava
syndrome.

28:45.462 --> 28:47.726
The catheter must have blocked
her SVC entirely.

28:47.769 --> 28:49.902
I'm taking it out.Can we take her
back to the IR suite

28:49.945 --> 28:51.686
and reposition it?No.

28:51.730 --> 28:53.340
How else
would she get dialysis?

28:53.383 --> 28:54.907
She wouldn't.Dr. Ndugu --

28:54.950 --> 28:56.604
She's already clotted off
multiple access points.

28:56.647 --> 28:57.910
Who's to say
it wouldn't happen again?

28:57.953 --> 28:59.389
Page Dr. Krause!

28:59.433 --> 29:00.956
♪♪

29:06.832 --> 29:09.704
It's fine. Everyone's watching.
That's what happens.

29:09.748 --> 29:11.967
People watch, you screw up,

29:12.011 --> 29:15.057
and then you quit and
go find a rock to hide under.

29:15.101 --> 29:17.712
[ NEEDTOBREATHE's "Alive"
plays ]

29:17.756 --> 29:19.279
Richard: You ready?

29:19.322 --> 29:20.367
♪♪

29:20.410 --> 29:21.411
Scalpel.

29:21.455 --> 29:30.333
♪♪

29:30.377 --> 29:32.248
♪ Flashes of doubt
that grow into a rage ♪

29:32.292 --> 29:34.207
[ Cheers and applause]

29:34.250 --> 29:37.471
♪ Locked out the truth,
they keep your dreams at bay ♪

29:37.514 --> 29:41.083
♪ Don't stand there waitin'
for the time to come ♪

29:41.127 --> 29:45.305
♪ C'mon, c'mon, catch me,
we got miles to run ♪

29:45.348 --> 29:48.656
♪ We are alive, our skin
is leaving these bones ♪

29:48.699 --> 29:52.660
♪ Fire in the wind,
we're burning out of control ♪

29:52.703 --> 29:55.750
♪ We are the children
chasing wondrous thrills ♪

29:55.794 --> 29:59.841
♪ Chasing a vision, baby, like
we're running downhill, oh ♪

29:59.885 --> 30:05.151
♪♪

30:05.194 --> 30:08.589
Nice extraction, Schmitt.Thank you.

30:08.632 --> 30:10.156
3-0 chromic, please.

30:10.199 --> 30:18.468
♪♪

30:18.512 --> 30:23.865
♪♪

30:23.909 --> 30:25.127
[ Monitor beeps ]

30:25.171 --> 30:26.650
♪♪

30:26.694 --> 30:28.348
Doppler.

30:28.391 --> 30:29.740
Relax, Schmitt.

30:29.784 --> 30:31.830
If you're calm,
everyone else is calm.

30:31.873 --> 30:35.094
♪♪

30:35.137 --> 30:37.531
[ Suction gurgling ]

30:37.574 --> 30:38.967
♪ Someday this body's
gonna come to rest ♪

30:39.011 --> 30:40.708
[ Sighing ]
Oh, this can't happen.

30:40.751 --> 30:42.884
Come on, come on,
come on, come on. Think.

30:42.928 --> 30:45.191
You can do this. Think.

30:45.234 --> 30:48.063
♪ These hills take longer
than we think to get down ♪

30:48.107 --> 30:49.195
♪ So I'll get used to living
with my feet off the ground ♪

30:49.238 --> 30:50.544
Bailey:
I'm turning the speaker on.

30:50.587 --> 30:52.459
Help him out, people.

30:52.502 --> 30:54.635
Are you getting a good signal
from the adjacent segments?

30:54.678 --> 30:56.463
Levi: Yes, both sides.

30:56.506 --> 30:58.291
Resect that segment.
Do a hand-sewn --

30:58.334 --> 30:59.466
End to end anastomosis.

30:59.509 --> 31:01.207
Uh, stapler.

31:01.250 --> 31:03.426
♪ Fire in the wind,
we're burning out of control ♪

31:03.470 --> 31:04.950
♪ We are the children
chasing wondrous thrills ♪

31:04.993 --> 31:07.039
To close, start bringing
the bowel together

31:07.082 --> 31:09.084
with a vicryl suture,
coming around the corner

31:09.128 --> 31:10.738
with a Connell stitch and --Taryn: And a 3 millimeter gap

31:10.781 --> 31:12.479
between every two sutures.

31:12.522 --> 31:13.654
Levi: Got it.

31:13.697 --> 31:15.177
[ Panting ]
Suction, Taryn --

31:15.221 --> 31:16.178
Dr. Helm.

31:16.222 --> 31:17.658
[ Suction gurgling ]

31:17.701 --> 31:27.015
♪♪

31:27.059 --> 31:28.234
What happened?

31:28.277 --> 31:29.975
There was a complication
from the catheter,

31:30.018 --> 31:31.846
so I had to remove it.So you'll reinsert it?

31:31.890 --> 31:34.501
I won't. And because we couldn't
gain access for dialysis,

31:34.544 --> 31:37.199
Rashida needs to be placed on
the transplant list immediately.

31:37.243 --> 31:38.679
Rashida's been my patient
for months.

31:38.722 --> 31:39.941
These aren't
your decisions to make.

31:39.985 --> 31:41.464
Except that now
she's also my patient.

31:41.508 --> 31:44.685
And she has suffered from
multiple unnecessary procedures,

31:44.728 --> 31:46.078
so I'm not putting her through
even more.

31:46.121 --> 31:47.209
This is not protocol.

31:47.253 --> 31:49.820
It's not. It's a life.

31:49.864 --> 31:51.387
Rashida's.

31:51.431 --> 31:55.696
♪♪

31:55.739 --> 31:57.045
Even if we list her,

31:57.089 --> 31:59.134
we don't know
when a kidney will come through.

31:59.178 --> 32:01.441
It'll come faster
than if we didn't.

32:01.484 --> 32:03.399
♪♪

32:03.443 --> 32:05.662
Oh, Hayes, uh, I'm looking
for Danny and Noah.

32:05.706 --> 32:07.838
Uh, they left.

32:07.882 --> 32:10.972
What do you mean they left?
I didn't discharge Noah.

32:11.016 --> 32:12.104
No, but I discharged
his son,

32:12.147 --> 32:15.063
and he said he wanted
to go home with him.

32:15.107 --> 32:17.196
So you just let him go?
Without asking me?

32:17.239 --> 32:18.719
He said he declined
all further testing,

32:18.762 --> 32:20.677
and then he signed an AMA.

32:20.721 --> 32:22.505
He has severe fibrosis
in both lungs.

32:22.549 --> 32:25.030
He needs supplementary oxygen,
a full pulmonary workup,

32:25.073 --> 32:26.379
an evaluation
by a specialist,

32:26.422 --> 32:28.033
and we're gonna need to do
more studies, okay,

32:28.076 --> 32:30.339
if we're gonna --Hunt, he's terminal.

32:30.383 --> 32:32.341
[ Sighs ]You know that, I know that,

32:32.385 --> 32:34.343
Noah knows that,
and he's accepted that.

32:34.387 --> 32:35.475
Hayes, just --Which is very difficult to do

32:35.518 --> 32:36.693
when you've got
a little one at home.

32:36.737 --> 32:38.478
Believe me.

32:38.521 --> 32:40.523
♪♪

32:40.567 --> 32:42.047
All those things you want to do
for him, they take time.

32:42.090 --> 32:44.353
They take energy.

32:44.397 --> 32:45.964
They're two things Noah wants
to give his son right now

32:46.007 --> 32:48.575
while he still can.

32:48.618 --> 32:51.012
Look, I'm sorry
I didn't ask you,

32:51.056 --> 32:52.971
but I'm not sorry
I let him go.

32:53.014 --> 32:58.628
♪♪

32:58.672 --> 33:00.761
[ Siren wailing, horns honking
in distance ]

33:00.804 --> 33:07.028
♪♪

33:07.072 --> 33:13.295
♪♪

33:13.339 --> 33:15.558
You look amazing.

33:15.602 --> 33:18.692
But, yeah,
you may want to change.

33:18.735 --> 33:20.346
[ Chuckles ]

33:21.956 --> 33:24.393
Sorry.

33:24.437 --> 33:25.786
It's okay.

33:31.879 --> 33:34.055
Listen.
You hear that?

33:34.099 --> 33:36.579
[ Insects chirping ]

33:36.623 --> 33:39.843
Meredith: What?Exactly.

33:39.887 --> 33:43.804
I mean, this right here, this is
why I pulled back on my hours.

33:43.847 --> 33:48.287
I was -- I was ignoring
everything around me.

33:48.330 --> 33:49.549
You know?

33:49.592 --> 33:50.985
The perfect silence,

33:51.029 --> 33:53.031
the 2-mile hike through
the woods behind my house,

33:53.074 --> 33:56.512
just sitting here, sitting,
staring up at the stars.

33:56.556 --> 33:58.775
♪♪

33:58.819 --> 34:01.082
I don't stargaze much.

34:01.126 --> 34:02.388
I'm sorry, since when?

34:02.431 --> 34:03.737
Since ever.

34:03.780 --> 34:05.913
Ooh, we're gonna have
so much fun.

34:05.956 --> 34:07.871
[ Chuckles ]
I've got so much to teach you.

34:07.915 --> 34:11.397
[ Laughs ]

34:11.440 --> 34:14.922
Hey, tell me about
this, um, top-secret project.

34:14.965 --> 34:16.924
Well, If I told you,
it wouldn't be top-secret.

34:16.967 --> 34:18.578
Fine.
Tell me one thing.

34:18.621 --> 34:21.494
You really struggle
with the concept of secrets.

34:21.537 --> 34:23.539
I guess I do.

34:23.583 --> 34:25.802
[ Sighs ]

34:25.846 --> 34:27.674
I'm scared to say yes.

34:27.717 --> 34:29.110
Hm.

34:29.154 --> 34:32.113
And I am
very rarely scared.

34:32.157 --> 34:36.857
♪♪

34:36.900 --> 34:39.338
What are you scared of?

34:39.381 --> 34:40.774
Failure.

34:42.167 --> 34:45.735
This project will cost
millions of dollars,

34:45.779 --> 34:48.347
will be very risky,

34:48.390 --> 34:50.914
win or lose, will eventually
be written about.

34:50.958 --> 34:52.568
And I'm just not sure

34:52.612 --> 34:55.615
that I want the first thing
that I do after surviving COVID

34:55.658 --> 34:57.182
to be a public failure.

34:57.225 --> 35:00.359
And I know that's my ego.

35:00.402 --> 35:03.492
I have a very comfortable
situation in Seattle.

35:03.536 --> 35:05.842
I have safety.
I have comfort.

35:05.886 --> 35:08.410
And now you're gonna
trade all of that in.

35:08.454 --> 35:10.847
You're gonna risk it all.

35:10.891 --> 35:12.806
Listen, you're not
a safety person, Meredith.

35:12.849 --> 35:14.721
You're not
a comfort person.

35:14.764 --> 35:16.505
It's not your nature.How do youknow?

35:16.549 --> 35:18.855
Because it's not mine, either.
And it takes one to know one.

35:18.899 --> 35:20.379
[ Chuckles ]

35:20.422 --> 35:22.990
You're gonna risk it all,
and win or lose...

35:23.033 --> 35:25.471
it's gonna be
a hell of a ride.

35:25.514 --> 35:30.911
♪♪

35:30.954 --> 35:33.261
[ Sirens wailing in distance ]

35:33.305 --> 35:36.960
Winston: I'm really sorry
to say this, Rashida.

35:37.004 --> 35:41.008
We couldn't gain access
for your dialysis.

35:41.051 --> 35:45.534
But...you're on
the transplant list, Rashida.

35:45.578 --> 35:49.582
[ Exhales sharply ]
Wait, what?

35:49.625 --> 35:51.018
Are you serious?

35:51.061 --> 35:52.324
Yeah.

35:53.760 --> 35:56.154
[ Sighs ] Wow.

35:56.197 --> 35:58.373
♪♪

35:58.417 --> 36:01.159
[ Breathes deeply ]

36:01.202 --> 36:02.725
[ Voice breaking ]
I honestly never thought

36:02.769 --> 36:04.684
I would see this day.

36:04.727 --> 36:07.730
You're not just
saving my life.

36:07.774 --> 36:10.472
You're changing it.

36:10.516 --> 36:13.954
I can go back to who I was.

36:13.997 --> 36:15.651
I don't know
how to thank you.

36:15.695 --> 36:17.436
[ Breathes deeply ]

36:17.479 --> 36:19.264
I can't wait
to tell everyone.

36:19.307 --> 36:21.396
[ Breathes deeply ]
Oh, and, Dr. Ndugu,

36:21.440 --> 36:24.051
when my followers find out
how you helped me --

36:24.094 --> 36:25.705
[ Sniffles ]
Are you single?

36:25.748 --> 36:27.228
[ Chuckles ]
I'm not.

36:27.272 --> 36:29.404
I'm actually married to
another cardiothoracic surgeon

36:29.448 --> 36:31.493
at this hospital --
Dr. Pierce.

36:31.537 --> 36:32.538
And she fly.

36:32.581 --> 36:33.626
What?
Mm-hmm.

36:33.669 --> 36:34.844
A cute doctor couple?

36:34.888 --> 36:36.194
Mm-hmm.
Okay!

36:36.237 --> 36:38.152
[ Chuckles ]I gotta meet her ASAP.

36:38.196 --> 36:39.936
Ooh, have you guys ever thought
about becoming influencers?

36:39.980 --> 36:41.938
The brands
would come flocking.

36:41.982 --> 36:44.419
Influencers?
For what? Health?

36:44.463 --> 36:46.247
Yeah, I mean, there are
influencers for everything.

36:46.291 --> 36:48.684
Okay, movies,
restaurants, plants.

36:48.728 --> 36:50.860
[ Chuckles ]
There are dog influencers, too.

36:50.904 --> 36:54.168
Mm-hmm. Biggie the Pug
has 2 million followers.

36:54.212 --> 36:56.605
Ha! Come on. Okay.
We gotta go live.

36:56.649 --> 36:57.650
Hey!

36:57.693 --> 36:59.695
Hey.
Ah!

36:59.739 --> 37:01.871
I haven't seen them this happy
in months.

37:01.915 --> 37:05.440
[ Chuckles ] Helm's
more thrilled than Schmitt.

37:05.484 --> 37:07.834
He let her keep the crystal.[ Chuckles ]

37:07.877 --> 37:10.053
And you seem to be
the happiest of them all.

37:10.097 --> 37:12.882
Feels good to be back,
in front of them.

37:12.926 --> 37:15.885
Well, Dr. Wong gave me
his retirement notice today.

37:15.929 --> 37:17.626
Dr. Wong?
He used to be a student of mine.

37:17.670 --> 37:18.584
Is something wrong?

37:18.627 --> 37:20.499
Healthy as a horse.

37:20.542 --> 37:22.588
And it's getting worse,
Richard.

37:22.631 --> 37:26.069
Every day, someone retires or
quits or moves to Minnesota...

37:26.113 --> 37:27.462
We don't know
if that's happening.

37:27.506 --> 37:30.465
[ Sighs ] Whether
it's burnout or exhaustion

37:30.509 --> 37:32.380
or just needing a change,

37:32.424 --> 37:34.817
these residents aren't the only
ones that need to reset.

37:34.861 --> 37:37.951
This whole hospital needs
to remember why we're here.

37:37.994 --> 37:40.301
COVID took that from us.

37:40.345 --> 37:42.999
You know, remember when we
used to have, like, pizza night

37:43.043 --> 37:45.611
and retreats, and -- and
residents would prank each other

37:45.654 --> 37:46.742
and --You hated that.

37:46.786 --> 37:48.309
But there was joy

37:48.353 --> 37:51.138
and the feeling that we were
all in this together,

37:51.181 --> 37:52.792
for something
bigger than ourselves.

37:52.835 --> 37:54.184
I want to
make room for that.

37:54.228 --> 37:56.012
I want to make space
for that again.

37:56.056 --> 38:00.495
You want people
to remember the why.

38:00.539 --> 38:02.497
So do I.

38:02.541 --> 38:05.283
♪ Feels just like
we're dreaming wide awake ♪

38:05.326 --> 38:06.980
I got some ideas, Bailey.

38:07.023 --> 38:07.850
♪ And I know we're only going

38:07.894 --> 38:08.851
♪ Up, up, up

38:08.895 --> 38:10.157
Big ones.

38:10.200 --> 38:11.637
♪ Here we go

38:11.680 --> 38:13.203
♪♪

38:13.247 --> 38:14.814
♪ Oooh ♪

38:14.857 --> 38:18.992
♪ And if that mockingbird
don't sing ♪[ Scout crying ]

38:19.035 --> 38:22.822
♪ Daddy's gonna buy you
a diamond ring ♪

38:22.865 --> 38:26.652
♪ And if all of those rings
don't work ♪

38:26.695 --> 38:29.785
♪ Daddy's gonna feel
like a big old jerk ♪

38:29.829 --> 38:34.137
Okay, you need to stop
with the depressing lullabies.

38:34.181 --> 38:35.965
Put him to sleep.[ Sighs ]

38:39.099 --> 38:43.321
Link, I-I know
that you are upset

38:43.364 --> 38:48.021
and sad and grieving
the future you thought you had.

38:48.064 --> 38:50.371
Obviously,
I have been there.

38:50.415 --> 38:52.068
And what did you do?

38:53.853 --> 38:58.074
I looked for joy
anywhere that I could.

38:59.337 --> 39:02.601
Then along came [sighs]
OB...

39:02.644 --> 39:04.080
and Luna.

39:06.344 --> 39:10.870
I know that it sucks right now,
but you're gonna be okay.

39:10.913 --> 39:13.786
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh, ooh,
ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh-ooh ♪

39:13.829 --> 39:15.570
♪♪

39:15.614 --> 39:19.400
Something didhappen
earlier with Leo.

39:19.444 --> 39:22.969
I-I-I thought a parent was being
judgy about his Elsa costume,

39:23.012 --> 39:25.014
so I-I confronted him.Who was it?

39:25.058 --> 39:27.016
No, no one.
He wasn't being judgy.

39:27.060 --> 39:30.193
I'm just --
Owen, I'm worried.

39:30.237 --> 39:32.674
I --

39:32.718 --> 39:36.330
I-I want Leo
to be okay in the world,

39:36.374 --> 39:39.377
and I'm -- I'm --
I'm worried, what if we...

39:39.420 --> 39:41.770
What if we let him
be himself?

39:41.814 --> 39:45.078
I'm worried that
the world won't be kind.

39:45.121 --> 39:47.123
I'm worried that
it will be hard.

39:47.167 --> 39:49.952
I'm worried
that people will be cruel.

39:49.996 --> 39:50.953
♪ No, I don't wanna be
so lonely... ♪

39:50.997 --> 39:52.433
And maybe they will be.

39:52.477 --> 39:54.348
♪ ...frozen

39:54.392 --> 39:55.654
But we won't be.

39:55.697 --> 39:57.960
Leo's happy. Let's --

39:58.004 --> 39:59.484
Let's just
let him be happy, okay?

39:59.527 --> 40:00.920
Okay.

40:00.963 --> 40:02.487
Leo: Mommy!Oh, there he is.

40:02.530 --> 40:03.966
Hey!
Hey!

40:04.010 --> 40:06.186
[ Chuckles ]Hey. How are you?
[ Grunts ]

40:06.229 --> 40:08.057
Look what I got.[ Both gasp ]

40:08.101 --> 40:10.930
Whoa.A new cape for Elsa,

40:10.973 --> 40:12.801
the Snow Queen.

40:12.845 --> 40:13.802
You like it?

40:13.846 --> 40:15.064
Yeah.

40:15.108 --> 40:16.675
I love it.

40:16.718 --> 40:18.720
[ Chuckling ] Hi!

40:18.764 --> 40:19.547
You got her?
Yeah.

40:19.591 --> 40:21.419
I'll take him. Hi!

40:21.462 --> 40:23.377
Hi!

40:23.421 --> 40:24.726
Let's go home.Okay.

40:24.770 --> 40:27.599
♪ I have no one left to blame
in the end ♪

40:27.642 --> 40:29.296
How was your day?Ah.

40:29.339 --> 40:31.341
♪ Yeah, I'm awake

40:31.385 --> 40:35.215
Meredith: There is such a thing
as predictive homeostasis.

40:35.258 --> 40:36.695
Late night.

40:36.738 --> 40:38.827
♪ Ooh-ooh-ooh, ooh

40:38.871 --> 40:40.133
♪ I'm awake

40:40.176 --> 40:41.482
You don't own me.

40:41.526 --> 40:42.875
Mm, I know.

40:42.918 --> 40:44.485
I need autonomy
picking the team.

40:44.529 --> 40:46.444
Absolutely.

40:46.487 --> 40:49.185
I'd like any progress
that we make from this process

40:49.229 --> 40:52.493
to be public and accessible
to everyone with Parkinson's.

40:52.537 --> 40:54.495
Of course.

40:54.539 --> 40:58.978
It's when our body anticipates
responses to future challenges.

40:59.021 --> 41:01.720
I'd like to move
the whole project to Grey-Sloan.

41:01.763 --> 41:04.418
Mnh. That I can't do.

41:04.462 --> 41:06.942
It's -- It's expensive.

41:06.986 --> 41:09.945
Frankly,
I don't have the time.

41:09.989 --> 41:11.947
We have
everything we need here.

41:11.991 --> 41:13.514
I can't
move to Minnesota.

41:13.558 --> 41:16.169
I need you here
as much as possible.

41:16.212 --> 41:17.431
♪ I can't see
the road I'm driving ♪

41:17.475 --> 41:18.650
